# mobile core

- Adapt to the existing project architecture before proposing a new one. Prefer consistency with the current codebase over enforcing an idealized folder tree.
- Keep state flow explicit and predictable. Model loading, empty, error, offline, and retry states as first-class product states.
- Use platform-appropriate navigation patterns instead of improvising custom routing behavior.
- Treat permissions, lifecycle, background execution, storage, networking transitions, and crash risk as correctness concerns, not polish concerns.
- Optimize for responsiveness and avoid unnecessary rerenders, recompositions, rebuilds, or cross-thread work on UI-critical paths.
- Consider accessibility, device diversity, interaction ergonomics, and localization part of the feature, not follow-up work.
- Favor testable boundaries: business logic should be unit-testable, and critical flows should have targeted UI or integration coverage where practical.
- Keep shared mobile guidance principle-based. Let platform-specific rules handle framework details.
